\par
\b Proposed structure\b0\par
\pard\f1\fs18
framework/\par
  settings.py        # Environment and timeout configuration\par
  api_client.py      # Reusable API request wrapper\par
  pages.py           # Login and projects page objects\par
tests/\par
  api/               # API contract and authorization tests\par
  ui/                # Web user journeys and role/tenant checks\par
  integration/       # API-to-UI workflows\par
test_data/           # Non-sensitive example input data\par
docs/                # Test plan, approach, and execution report\par
.github/workflows/   # CI workflow\par
conftest.py          # pytest fixtures and browser/device options\par
\pard\f0\fs24\par
\b Design decisions\b0\par
\pard\li360
\bullet\tab pytest provides fixtures, markers, parameterization, test selection, and standard CI reporting.\par
\bullet\tab Playwright provides browser automation, automatic actionability checks, traces, screenshots, and modern locator APIs.\par
\bullet\tab Page objects keep selectors and reusable interactions out of business-focused tests.\par
\bullet\tab An API client centralizes authorization headers, tenant headers, request construction, and response handling.\par
\bullet\tab Data factories generate unique project names so parallel test runs do not collide.\par
\bullet\tab Environment values use environment variables and CI secrets; repository configuration contains no real credentials.\par
\pard\li0\par
\b Configuration management\b0\par
The suite reads WEB_BASE_URL, API_BASE_URL, user credentials, API tokens, browser, device, and timeout values from environment variables. Environment-specific values belong in a protected QA/staging secret store. Tests can run with --browser chromium, --browser firefox, or --browser webkit and with desktop or mobile-web viewports. BrowserStack credentials are CI secrets.\par
\par
\b Questions to clarify before scaling the framework\b0\par
\pard\li360
\bullet\tab Are tenants isolated by subdomain, database, tenant header, or a combination?\par
\bullet\tab Which browsers, versions, operating systems, and devices are officially supported?\par
\bullet\tab Is mobile a native app, responsive web, or both?\par
\bullet\tab Is there a resettable QA environment and a supported test-data cleanup API?\par
\bullet\tab How should test users complete 2FA safely?\par
\bullet\tab Are project creation and search eventually consistent or asynchronous?\par
\bullet\tab What are the allowed parallelism, execution-time budget, reporting format, and release gates?\par
\bullet\tab Which third-party integrations should be mocked in lower environments versus tested end-to-end?\par
\pard\li0\par
\b CI/CD and BrowserStack strategy\b0\par
Run API tests and a small Chromium smoke suite on every pull request. Run a risk-based BrowserStack matrix nightly: Chrome on Windows, Firefox on Windows, Safari on macOS, iPhone Safari, and Android Chrome. Retain JUnit XML, traces, screenshots, video, console logs, and failed API responses for failures. This preserves useful cross-platform coverage without running every scenario on every device for every pull request.\par
\par
\b Part 3 - API + UI Integration Test\b0\par
\par
\b Test strategy\b0\par
The integration flow creates a uniquely named project through the Company1 API, verifies that it is visible in Company1's web UI, validates the responsive mobile-web view, verifies that Company2 cannot retrieve it through the API, and removes the project in a finally block. A fresh browser context is used for each user session to prevent cookies or local storage from leaking between tenants.\par
\par
\b Integration test (illustrative code)\b0\par
\pard\f1\fs18
@pytest.mark.integration\par
@pytest.mark.tenant_isolation\par
def test_project_creation_flow(page, api_client, company1_user, company2_user):\par
    payload = \{\par
        "name": f"integration-project-{uuid.uuid4().hex[:8]}",\par
        "description": "Created by automated integration test",\par
        "team_members": [],\par
    \}\par
    project_id = None\par
    try:\par
        # 1. API: create project in Company1\par
        create = api_client.create_project(\par
            company1_user["token"], company1_user["tenant"], payload\par
        )\par
        assert create.status == 201, create.text()\par
        project_id = create.json()["id"]\par
\par
        # 2. Web UI: verify Company1 can see the new project\par
        login(page, company1_user["email"], company1_user["password"])\par
        open_projects(page)\par
        card = page.get_by_test_id(f"project-card-{project_id}")\par
        expect(card).to_be_visible()\par
        expect(card).to_contain_text(payload["name"])\par
        expect(card).to_have_attribute("data-tenant-id", "company1")\par
\par
        # 3. Mobile: run the same test using --device mobile-web\par
        # The fixture uses a 390x844 touch viewport for this execution.\par
\par
        # 4. Security: Company2 must not access Company1's project\par
        denied = api_client.get_project(\par
            company2_user["token"], company2_user["tenant"], project_id\par
        )\par
        assert denied.status in (403, 404)\par
    finally:\par
        if project_id is not None:\par
            cleanup = api_client.delete_project(\par
                company1_user["token"], company1_user["tenant"], project_id\par
            )\par
            assert cleanup.status in (200, 204), cleanup.text()\par
\pard\f0\fs24\par
\b Test-data and edge-case handling\b0\par
\pard\li360
\bullet\tab Each project gets a UUID-based name so data remains unique when tests execute in parallel.\par
\bullet\tab Cleanup happens in finally, including when a validation fails. A scheduled cleanup job is a second safeguard.\par
\bullet\tab API response status and payload are asserted immediately after creation, producing a useful failure message for network, authorization, or validation errors.\par
\bullet\tab UI checks wait for stable business-ready elements, not time delays. If project indexing is eventually consistent, the product should expose a defined ready signal or the test should poll only the specific project endpoint for a bounded period.\par
\bullet\tab Failed tests should collect traces, screenshots, video, browser console logs, and failed network responses.\par
\bullet\tab For native mobile apps, replace the responsive-browser fixture with Appium sessions on BrowserStack App Automate while retaining the same API setup and tenant-isolation assertions.\par
\pard\li0\par
\b Final note\b0\par
The repository contains the runnable implementation, test plan, example data, CI workflow, and execution-report template. Tests are not represented as run against Bynry systems because approved URLs, credentials, test data, and selectors were not available. This is deliberate: test results should never be fabricated.\par
